<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900709-0007</DOCNO><DOCID>900709-0007.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Says Satellites   May Be Launched   By Soviet Rockets</HL><DATE>07/09/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><CO>   UTX FREST</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- President Bush will permit, for the firsttime, U.S. commercial satellites to be launched by Sovietrockets, Secretary of State James Baker said.   Speaking on ABC-News' &quot;This Week&quot; program yesterday, Mr.Baker said he didn't know when the first American satellitewould be carried by a Soviet rocket, which would be launchedfrom Australia, but that the president had decided &quot;aninitial launch can go forward.&quot; The president's decision wasfirst reported by the New York Times.</LP><TEXT>   American rocket companies have opposed the competitionthat allowing U.S. satellites on Soviet rockets would bring.But the Soviets offer services to U.S. satellite companies atprices the companies feel they should take advantage of tostay competitive.   Meanwhile, USBI Co., a unit of United Technologies Corp.,reportedly is in line to receive an export license from theState Department to operate the Australian space port. AndreaShea-King, a USBI spokeswoman, confirmed yesterday thatUnited Technologies has been involved in studying andplanning the initiative for about three years. But she addedthat United Technologies has yet to be notified about thelicense approval.   USBI, with operations in Cape Canaveral, Fla., andHuntsville, Ala., is a major contractor to NASA for the SpaceShuttle program. Mrs. Shea-King said United Technologies wasone of three aerospace giants invited by the Australians tosubmit proposals, although she added that she didn't know theidentity of the rivals. &quot;To my knowledge, we are the onlyentity in the running now,&quot; she said.   While declining to provide details, the spokeswoman saidany forthcoming contract to serve as the program manager inAustralia would &quot;have a significant financial&quot; impact for thecompany.</TEXT></DOC>